Briefly describe the dataset:

The dataset contains data on avocado prices and sales volume in multiple cities, states and regions of the US. Some of the relevant columns in the dataset include the date the avocados were observed, the average price of a single avocado, type, the year, the city or region of the observed avocado, total number of avocados sold and total number of avocados with PLU.

import plotnine as p9
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, labs, geom_boxplot

#Filter dataset by geography and obtain the average total volume of avocados sold. Sort by largest to smallest city
city_avgs=filter.groupby('geography')['total_volume'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)

#give the top 5 cities 
top_5 = city_avgs.head(5).index

#create a new dataframe
df_top_5 = filter[filter["geography"].isin(top_5)]

(
    ggplot(df_top_5, aes(x='geography', y='total_volume'))
    + geom_boxplot()
    + labs(title='Top 5 Metro Cities by Average Total Volume')
)

Los Angeles has the largest overall average out of the top 5 metro cities in the US.

Code 
avocados = ['xlarge', 'large', 'small']

# Aggregating prices by PLU and type (conventional/organic)
aggregate = df_california.groupby(['geography', 'type'])[avocados].mean().reset_index()

#change dataset wide to long 
price_proportion=aggregate.melt(id_vars=['geography', 'type'], var_name='size', value_name='average_price')

#totals per region/type
total_price = (
    price_proportion
    .groupby(['geography', 'type'], as_index=False)['average_price']
    .sum()
    .rename(columns={'average_price': 'sum'}))

#merge the proportions
price_proportion=price_proportion.merge(total_price, on=['geography', 'type'])
price_proportion['proportion'] = price_proportion['average_price']/price_proportion['sum']

9.Using outside data - find or assemble a dataset of real data, with house prices for these four California regions. Join this dataset with California avocado dataset

Code 
from plotnine import *

house_prices = pd.read_csv('HousingPriceIndex.csv')

#filter out only the cities in California - 4 metro cities in California
california_housing = ['San Francisco-San Mateo-Redwood City, CA (MSAD)', 'San Diego-Chula Vista-Carlsbad, CA', 'Sacramento-Roseville-Folsom, CA', 'Los Angeles-Long Beach-Glendale, CA (MSAD)']

house_prices = house_prices[house_prices['place_name'].isin(california_housing)].copy()

#convert month to be numeric
house_prices['month'] = pd.to_numeric(house_prices['period'], errors='coerce').astype('Int64')

#map out the city names from housing dataset to make sure they match the names to df-california
cities = {
    'San Francisco-San Mateo-Redwood City, CA (MSAD)': 'San Francisco',
    'San Diego-Chula Vista-Carlsbad, CA': 'San Diego',
    'Sacramento-Roseville-Folsom, CA': 'Sacramento',
    'Los Angeles-Long Beach-Glendale, CA (MSAD)': 'Los Angeles'
}
house_prices['geography'] = house_prices['place_name'].replace(cities)

#remove the unecessary columns 
house_cols = (
    house_prices[['geography', 'yr', 'month', 'index_sa']]
    .rename(columns={'yr':'year', 'index_sa':'house_cost'}
))
#filter from 2015-2020
house_cols = house_cols[(house_cols['year'] >= 2015) & (house_cols['year'] <= 2020)]

#convert avocado data into a monthly format 
avocado_date = df_california.copy()
avocado_date['date'] = pd.to_datetime(avocado_date['date'], errors='coerce')
avocado_date = avocado_date.dropna(subset=['date'])
avocado_date['year'] = avocado_date['date'].dt.year
avocado_date['month'] = avocado_date['date'].dt.month

#average prices per city
#I had to look up how to rename the columns 
avocado_prices = (
     avocado_date
        .groupby(['geography', 'year', 'month'], as_index=False)['average_price']
        .mean()
        .rename(columns={'average_price': 'avocado_cost'})
)

#inner join to merge housing with avocado dataset
merged_set = (
    avocado_prices.merge(house_cols, on=['geography', 'year', 'month'], how='inner')
                .dropna(subset=['avocado_cost', 'house_cost'])
)

Plot

Code 
from plotnine import *
(
    ggplot(merged_set, aes(x='avocado_cost', y='house_cost', color='geography'))
    + geom_point()
    + geom_smooth(method='lm', se=False)
    + facet_wrap('~geography')
    #separate by city to show the correlation 
    + labs(
        title='Avocado vs. Housing Price Index', 
        x = 'Average Avocado Price', 
        y = 'House Price Index',
        color='Region'
    )
    )

Across all four metropolitan cities in California from 2015-2020, the linear regression model show a positive relationship for all cities. Each place with higher avocado prices also illustrate to have higher housing price index values. Although each have a positive correlation, San Francisco has a weaker correlation while Los Angeles and San Diego have a strong positive correlation, and Sacramento with a neutral correlation. Both values demonstrate the overall cost of living differences where it shows expensive markets have more expensive homes and pricier avocados.
